If you are suggesting that these &quot;played out&quot; threads be deleted to make room for other topics, I consider that a terrible idea. Even the ones that only has a few postings were considered important to somebody enough to start the thread. And as a teacher, you would understand the historical significance of these threads and posts. Probably the two most historically significant threads would be &quot;Protestors&quot; and &quot;attitudes towards U.S. Vietnamese&quot;, but this does not detract from other issues that others have brought forth. And, just as you had, many will come to review these threads to get a &quot;feel&quot; and, hopefully, will feel comfortable enough to jump in, just as you had. I had watched this site for about a month before feeling it out with a post of my own.<br><br>
When an individual, such as Lien, (on the &quot;attitudes&quot; thread) feels comfortable to start a thread, it probably is the greatest contribution they can make, aside from airing out their issues. Nobody knows whether or not a thread will take off until it is &quot;played out&quot;. I would have never guessed that the &quot;attitude&quot; thread would have gone the way it did. (nor would have Doc Spatz!)<br><br>
We still have the option of starting new threads, thanks to POV. When an issue comes to mind, new and fresh threads will come forth, along with new perspectives.<br><br>
I started the thread &quot;The Forgotten Warriors&quot; as I thought it was an important issue. The fact that it only has three posts to date does not change my mind about the importance of this issue. If I left it up to a public quorum, it might not have been posted. I would not have stood for that!<br><br>
I have no problems with a survey, however, to bounce ideas around, but as to what threads are started must be left to the individuals.
